Endpoint Detection and Response
(EDR/XDR)

Endpoint detection and response (EDR) tools monitor endpoint logs, running processes, media device usage, network connections to remote addresses, user account activities, etc. The term "Endpoint Detection and Response (EDR)" was first coined by computer security specialist Anton Chuvakin. They play a considerable role in incident response to detect and respond to attacks. 

Some may confuse EDR with HIDS! In a nutshell, EDR is the next generation of HIDS. It provides advanced capabilities and includes response functionalities that a HIDS lacks, such as isolating an infected endpoint from the network to prevent malware from spreading to other endpoints. EDRs also provide automation capabilities to help organizations analyze and detect threats at scale.

According to Stratistics MRC's Endpoint Detection and Response:

"Global Market Outlook (2017-2026), sales of EDR solutionsboth on-premises and cloud-basedare expected to reach $7.27 billion by 2026, with an annual growth rate of nearly 26%." 

Endpoint Detection and response solutions rely on agents installed on endpoints to monitor endpoint activities and report back to a centralized server. Some EDRs utilize artificial intelligence and machine learning to detect threat patterns. Please pay attention to vendors' claims and do not take them for granted; always ask for proof!

Some well-known commercial EDR platforms:

  • Sophos Intercept X: Next-Gen Endpoint
  • SentinelOne Singularity
  • MVISION Endpoint Security
  • CarbonBlack
     

 

Another open-source EDR still in the development phase is "OpenEDR."
 

According to OpenEDR:

"OpenEDR is free and its source code is open to the public. OpenEDR allows you to analyze what's happening across your entire environment at the base-security-event level. This granularity enables accurate root-causes analysis needed for faster and more effective remediation." 

Recently, a new terminology appeared in the market called extended EDR (XDR - extended detection and response). XDR tools have the same capabilities as EDR but with more enhancements.

It's vital to emphasize that you, as a defender, should not care about what a vendor names its solution. You will hear tons of new buzzwords and jargon each day! Your focus should be on finding a solution that meets your requirements and the ability to evaluate products technically and unbiasedly.
